      Private funds
   =20
 =20
The traditional trade-off in U.S. capital markets is:=09If you are a public=
 company, you are very regulated and have to do lots of public disclosure, =
but you are free to raise lots of money by selling stock to anyone you want=
.=09If you are a private company, you are not particularly regulated and do=
n=E2=80=99t have to do much disclosure, but you can only sell stock to a re=
stricted pool of rich people and institutional investors, which limits your=
 ability to raise money.It is in most respects more pleasant to be private,=
 but there is more money in public markets. So traditionally companies stay=
ed private until they needed to raise a lot of money to grow larger, and th=
en they went public. Or they would stay private until their=C2=A0private sh=
areholders=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0mainly venture-capital investors, founders a=
nd employees =E2=80=94=C2=A0wanted to sell their shares, which again is muc=
h easier to do in public markets.=C2=A0Sometimes companies would go public =
for other reasons (vanity, added credibility with customers and employees, =
etc.), and sometimes companies would have enough internally generated cash =
or private financing to stay private even while growing huge, but for the m=
ost part the traditional deal was that being private avoided disclosure rul=
es but being public was where the money was.That has changed in recent year=
s, as we have often discussed: There is a ton of money in private markets, =
so there is less need for companies to go public to raise money or offer li=
quidity to their early investors. And because being public is still general=
ly less pleasant and more regulated than being private, companies have a te=
ndency to stay private longer, and there are more very large private compan=
ies. (=E2=80=9CThere Are Now 1,000 Unicorn Startups Worth $1 Billion or Mor=
e,=E2=80=9D Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Ellen Huet  reported this week.)=C2=A0How s=
hould you react to this? One possible reaction is =E2=80=9Cseems fine.=E2=
=80=9D Another is: =E2=80=9CThis is bad for regular public investors, who h=
ave lost access to growing companies, so we should encourage more companies=
 to go public by making it easier, more pleasant and less regulated.=E2=80=
=9D (This is roughly speaking the approach that Jay Clayton, the previous h=
ead of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission,  endorsed.) Another is:=
 =E2=80=9CThis is bad for regular public investors, so we should encourage =
more companies to go public by making it=C2=A0harder to stay private.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0Another is: =E2=80=9CThis is bad for=C2=A0private investors, becau=
se they do not have the same protections and audited financial statements t=
hat public-company investors have.=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CThis is bad for=C2=
=A0the public, because they have less information with which to hold big pr=
ivate companies accountable.=E2=80=9D Or, cynically: =E2=80=9CThis is bad f=
or=C2=A0the SEC, because it has fewer levers with which to regulate big pri=
vate companies.=E2=80=9D If those are your views, you might want to encoura=
ge more private companies to go public (by making it more pleasant to be pu=
blic or less pleasant to be private). Or you might just want to=C2=A0regula=
te private companies more, and try to subject them to more rules to (1) pro=
tect their investors, (2) inform and empower the public and (3) give the SE=
C more power.=C2=A0We  talked last month about stories that =E2=80=9Cthe SE=
C, Wall Street=E2=80=99s top regulator, has begun work on a plan to require=
 more private companies to routinely disclose information about their finan=
ces and operations=E2=80=9D:=E2=80=9CWhen they=E2=80=99re big firms, they c=
an have a huge impact on thousands of people=E2=80=99s lives with absolutel=
y no visibility for investors, employees and their unions, regulators, or t=
he public,=E2=80=9D said Democratic SEC Commissioner Allison Lee, who has c=
alled for the change.=C2=A0This is a theory that=C2=A0bigness requires SEC =
regulation. The traditional theory is that companies get to choose: They ca=
n be SEC-regulated in exchange for access to public markets, or they can de=
cline SEC regulation[1] and lose access to public markets. The theory of th=
e current SEC, under Chair Gary Gensler,=C2=A0is a significant departure fr=
om that: It suggests that the SEC might have the right to impose disclosure=
 rules on any=C2=A0company, if it decides that that disclosure is in the pu=
blic interest.[2] Companies do not have the power to opt in or out of SEC d=
isclosure regimes; that=E2=80=99s a decision for the SEC.There is an entire=
ly parallel story to be told about investment=C2=A0funds. If you are an inv=
estment manager, you can run a public mutual fund (or exchange-traded fund)=
, which lets you raise money from anybody but subjects you to lots of regul=
ation about investment choices, leverage, disclosure, conflicts of interest=
, etc. Or you can run a private fund =E2=80=94=C2=A0a hedge fund, private e=
quity fund, venture capital fund, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0which limits you to r=
aising money from rich people or institutional investors but frees you to n=
egotiate whatever terms you want with them. You want to raise a fund that w=
ill invest in whatever you want, charge whatever fees you want and never te=
ll investors anything? If you can convince, like, the head of the Yale endo=
wment to give you money for that, go right ahead.Of course even here there =
are limits, but they are mostly not limits imposed by specific SEC rules. T=
he main limits are:=09If you lie to your investors that=E2=80=99s securitie=
s fraud and the SEC can come after you.=09If you are an investment manager =
you probably have state-law fiduciary duties to your clients, so if you swi=
ndle them you will get in trouble.So mutual funds can be much larger than h=
edge funds and private equity funds, but their relationships with their cli=
ents are much more regulated. And you can opt in to public-fund-type disclo=
sure and conflicts regulation if you want public money, or you can opt out =
and take only sophisticated private money.And in recent years there is a lo=
t=C2=A0of private money, and it is not always all that sophisticated, and p=
rivate funds have become bigger and more influential, and there have been v=
arious scandals in which they have done things that look a bit rude to thei=
r clients. In particular, the SEC has sometimes brought securities-fraud-ty=
pe enforcement actions against private equity firms for charging sneaky fee=
s to their client funds and portfolio companies. In  writing about those  c=
ases, I have sometimes been skeptical that they were actually=C2=A0fraud. T=
he private equity firms=C2=A0disclosed=C2=A0the fees, everything was more o=
r less permitted by their contracts with investors, but it just felt a litt=
le icky. There were asymmetries of power or sophistication that made the cl=
ients not so great at protecting themselves, and the SEC stepped in to prot=
ect them in ways that maybe went a bit beyond its usual anti-fraud mandate.=
=C2=A0But you could =E2=80=94=C2=A0Gary Gensler=E2=80=99s SEC could =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0take a broader view. The broader view is: Look, private investment=
 funds are large and important, their clients are often socially important =
institutions (pension funds etc.), the SEC=E2=80=99s job is to protect thos=
e clients, and so the SEC should have more comprehensive rules about privat=
e funds=E2=80=99 practices. Those private funds should have to give their c=
lients standardized regular financial disclosures, like public funds do; th=
ere should be rules restricting their conflicts of interest and fees and ge=
nerally protecting their clients. The rules would be less restrictive than =
the rules for public mutual funds, because the private investors are more s=
ophisticated, but they=E2=80=99d be similar in kind. The SEC=E2=80=99s job =
is to protect all investors, and if private equity investors aren=E2=80=99t=
 doing a good job of protecting themselves the SEC will.So:Regulators propo=
sed expansive new requirements for private investment funds Wednesday as pa=
rt of a widening effort to police a rapidly growing but relatively opaque c=
orner of the capital markets.In a Wednesday morning meeting, the Securities=
 and Exchange Commission passed a proposal that would force hedge funds and=
