<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note: </strong><em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><table class=3D"header" =
width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Private funds</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The traditional trade-off in U.S. capi=
tal markets is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40p=
x; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are a publi=
c company, you are very regulated and have to do lots of public disclosure,=
 but you are free to raise lots of money by selling stock to anyone you wan=
t.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are a private company, y=
ou are not particularly regulated and don=E2=80=99t have to do much disclos=
ure, but you can only sell stock to a restricted pool of rich people and in=
stitutional investors, which limits your ability to raise money.</li></ol><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is in most respects more pleasant to be priv=
ate, but there is more money in public markets. So traditionally companies =
stayed private until they needed to raise a lot of money to grow larger, an=
d then they went public. Or they would stay private until their=C2=A0<em>pr=
ivate shareholders=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0mainly venture-capital investor=
s, founders and employees =E2=80=94=C2=A0wanted to sell their shares, which=
 again is much easier to do in public markets.=C2=A0Sometimes companies wou=
ld go public for other reasons (vanity, added credibility with customers an=
d employees, etc.), and sometimes companies would have enough internally ge=
nerated cash or private financing to stay private even while growing huge, =
but for the most part the traditional deal was that being private avoided d=
isclosure rules but being public was where the money was.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">That has changed in recent years, as we have often discussed=
: There is a ton of money in private markets, so there is less need for com=
panies to go public to raise money or offer liquidity to their early invest=
ors. And because being public is still generally less pleasant and more reg=
ulated than being private, companies have a tendency to stay private longer=
, and there are more very large private companies. (=E2=80=9CThere Are Now =
1,000 Unicorn Startups Worth $1 Billion or More,=E2=80=9D Bloomberg=E2=80=
=99s Ellen Huet <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26=
666543.270608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjItM=
DItMDkvdGhlcmUtYXJlLW5vdy0xLTAwMC11bmljb3JuLXByaXZhdGUtY29tcGFueS1zdGFydHVw=
cy13b3J0aC0xLWJpbGxpb24tb3ItbW9yZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjEwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1=
fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAyMTAmdXRtX2=
NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB63f10e8f" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> repor=
ted this week</a>.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How should you re=
act to this? One possible reaction is =E2=80=9Cseems fine.=E2=80=9D Another=
 is: =E2=80=9CThis is bad for regular public investors, who have lost acces=
s to growing companies, so we should encourage more companies to go public =
by making it easier, more pleasant and less regulated.=E2=80=9D (This is ro=
ughly speaking the approach that Jay Clayton, the previous head of the U.S.=
 Securities and Exchange Commission, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/26666543.270608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDctMTMvbWFpbi1zdHJlZXQtYW5kLXByZW1pdW0tbGlzdGluZ3M=
_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW=
5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB88bc1212" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> endorsed</a>.) Another is: =E2=80=9CThi=
s is bad for regular public investors, so we should encourage more companie=
s to go public by making it=C2=A0<em>harder to stay private.</em>=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another is: =E2=80=9CThis is bad for=
=C2=A0<em>private investors</em>, because they do not have the same protect=
ions and audited financial statements that public-company investors have.=
=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CThis is bad for=C2=A0<em>the public</em>, because th=
ey have less information with which to hold big private companies accountab=
le.=E2=80=9D Or, cynically: =E2=80=9CThis is bad for=C2=A0<em>the SEC</em>,=
 because it has fewer levers with which to regulate big private companies.=
=E2=80=9D If those are your views, you might want to encourage more private=
 companies to go public (by making it more pleasant to be public or less pl=
easant to be private). Or you might just want to=C2=A0<em>regulate private =
companies more</em>, and try to subject them to more rules to (1) protect t=
heir investors, (2) inform and empower the public and (3) give the SEC more=
 power.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26666543.270608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMTEvd2hvLWNhbi1yZXNpc3QtdGhlLWNyeXB=
0by1ib29tP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3=
NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDIxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZ=
g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB08b0d62e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked last month</a> about s=
tories that =E2=80=9Cthe SEC, Wall Street=E2=80=99s top regulator, has begu=
n work on a plan to require more private companies to routinely disclose in=
formation about their finances and operations=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhen they=E2=80=99re big firms, they can =
have a huge impact on thousands of people=E2=80=99s lives with absolutely n=
o visibility for investors, employees and their unions, regulators, or the =
public,=E2=80=9D said Democratic SEC Commissioner Allison Lee, who has call=
ed for the change.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This =
is a theory that=C2=A0<em>bigness requires SEC regulation</em>. The traditi=
onal theory is that companies get to choose: They can be SEC-regulated in e=
xchange for access to public markets, or they can decline SEC regulation[1]=
 and lose access to public markets. The theory of the current SEC, under Ch=
air Gary Gensler,=C2=A0is a significant departure from that: It suggests th=
at the SEC might have the right to impose disclosure rules on <em>any=C2=A0=
</em>company, if it decides that that disclosure is in the public interest.=
[2] Companies do not have the power to opt in or out of SEC disclosure regi=
mes; that=E2=80=99s a decision for the SEC.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>There is an entirely parallel story to be told about investment=C2=A0<em>f=
unds</em>. If you are an investment manager, you can run a public mutual fu=
nd (or exchange-traded fund), which lets you raise money from anybody but s=
ubjects you to lots of regulation about investment choices, leverage, discl=
osure, conflicts of interest, etc. Or you can run a private fund =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0a hedge fund, private equity fund, venture capital fund, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0which limits you to raising money from rich people or institutiona=
l investors but frees you to negotiate whatever terms you want with them. Y=
ou want to raise a fund that will invest in whatever you want, charge whate=
ver fees you want and never tell investors anything? If you can convince, l=
ike, the head of the Yale endowment to give you money for that, go right ah=
ead.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course even here there are limits, =
but they are mostly not limits imposed by specific SEC rules. The main limi=
ts are:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margi=
n: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you lie to your investo=
rs that=E2=80=99s securities fraud and the SEC can come after you.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are an investment manager you proba=
bly have state-law fiduciary duties to your clients, so if you swindle them=
 you will get in trouble.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So mutual f=
unds can be <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/266665=
43.270608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3RhdGlzdGEuY29tL3N0YXRpc3RpY3MvMTI2MTc3Ny9sYXJnZ=
XN0LW11dHVhbC1mdW5kcy13b3JsZHdpZGUv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe3f812dd" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">much larger</a> than hedge funds and private equity funds, but their re=
lationships with their clients are much more regulated. And you can opt in =
to public-fund-type disclosure and conflicts regulation if you want public =
money, or you can opt out and take only sophisticated private money.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in recent years there is a lot=C2=A0of privat=
e money, and it is not always all that sophisticated, and private funds hav=
e become bigger and more influential, and there have been various scandals =
in which they have done things that look a bit rude to their clients. In pa=
rticular, the SEC has sometimes brought securities-fraud-type enforcement a=
ctions against private equity firms for charging sneaky fees to their clien=
t funds and portfolio companies. In <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/26666543.270608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMTAtMDcvc2VjLWZpbmRzLXRoYXQtYmxhY2tzdG9uZS1jaGFyZ2Vk=
LXRvby1tYW55LWZlZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWF=
pbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb2=
5leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5a88d85f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> writing</a> about th=
ose <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26666543.27060=
8/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDYtMjkva=
