lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> cases</a>, I have sometimes been skeptical that th=
ey were actually=C2=A0<em>fraud</em>. The private equity firms=C2=A0<em>dis=
closed=C2=A0</em>the fees, everything was more or less permitted by their c=
ontracts with investors, but it just felt a little icky. There were asymmet=
ries of power or sophistication that made the clients not so great at prote=
cting themselves, and the SEC stepped in to protect them in ways that maybe=
 went a bit beyond its usual anti-fraud mandate.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">But you could =E2=80=94=C2=A0Gary Gensler=E2=80=99s SEC could =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0take a broader view. The broader view is: Look, private inve=
stment funds are large and important, their clients are often socially impo=
rtant institutions (pension funds etc.), the SEC=E2=80=99s job is to protec=
t those clients, and so the SEC should have more comprehensive rules about =
private funds=E2=80=99 practices. Those private funds should have to give t=
heir clients standardized regular financial disclosures, like public funds =
do; there should be rules restricting their conflicts of interest and fees =
and generally protecting their clients. The rules would be <em>less </em>re=
strictive than the rules for public mutual funds, because the private inves=
tors are more sophisticated, but they=E2=80=99d be similar in kind. The SEC=
=E2=80=99s job is to protect all investors, and if private equity investors=
 aren=E2=80=99t doing a good job of protecting themselves the SEC will.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/26666543.270608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zZWMtdG8t=
cHJvcG9zZS1icm9hZC1kaXNjbG9zdXJlLXJ1bGVzLWZvci1wcml2YXRlLWludmVzdG1lbnQtZnV=
uZHMtMTE2NDQ0MTg4MDE_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc=
12344f0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">So</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Regula=
tors proposed expansive new requirements for private investment funds Wedne=
sday as part of a widening effort to police a rapidly growing but relativel=
y opaque corner of the capital markets.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In =
a Wednesday morning meeting, the Securities and Exchange Commission passed =
a proposal that would force hedge funds and private-equity funds to provide=
 basic disclosures to their investors and guard against conflicts. The Demo=
cratic-controlled commission approved the proposal by a 3-to-1 vote, signal=
ing a strong chance that a final version will be adopted. The agency will n=
ow seek public comments for at least two months before issuing a final rule=
. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wednesday=E2=80=99s proposal would ma=
rk a sea change. For the first time, private-fund managers would be require=
d to provide their investors with quarterly statements detailing fund perfo=
rmance, fees and expenses, as well as manager compensation. Funds would hav=
e to undergo annual audits, in an effort by the SEC to place a check on ass=
et-valuation estimates often used to calculate fund managers=E2=80=99 fees.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Gensler said the proposal reflects the=
 growing importance of private funds, which hold more than $18 trillion of =
gross assets. He noted that their investors include pension plans represent=
ing millions of Americans, as well as university endowments.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CPrivate fund advisers, through the funds they ma=
nage, touch so much of our economy,=E2=80=9D Mr. Gensler said. =E2=80=9CThu=
s, it=E2=80=99s worth asking whether we can promote more efficiency, compet=
ition, and transparency in this field.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Here are the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/26666543.270608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbG=
Vhc2UvMjAyMi0xOQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB53dce1c7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
