style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">fact sheet</a>. Basically the rules =
consist of some disclosure requirements and some miscellaneous prohibitions=
 on private equity fee practices that people have found distasteful in rece=
nt years. Here is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/26666543.270608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3N0YXRlbWVudC9wZWlyY2Utc=
3RhdGVtZW50LXByb3Bvc2VkLXByaXZhdGUtZnVuZC1hZHZpc2Vycy0wMjA5MjI/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBe7879b87" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">dissent </a>from Republican SEC Commissioner=
 Hester Peirce:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today=E2=80=99s=
 proposal represents a sea change. It embodies a belief that many sophistic=
ated institutions and high net worth individuals are not competent or asser=
tive enough to obtain and analyze the information they need to make good in=
vestment decisions or to structure appropriately their relationships with p=
rivate funds. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These changes represent a=
 meaningful recasting of the SEC=E2=80=99s mission. First, the proposal=E2=
=80=99s focus on protecting private fund investors by shaking information l=
oose from what=C2=A0<em>we</em>=C2=A0deem to be uncommunicative private fun=
ds and shutting down practices=C2=A0<em>we</em>=C2=A0deem to be unfair is a=
 departure from the Commission=E2=80=99s historical view that these types o=
f investors can fend for themselves.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s crazy to think that sometimes pen=
sion funds=C2=A0<em>have </em>fended imperfectly for themselves in dealing =
with private investment funds. But it really is a big change to suggest tha=
t it=E2=80=99s the SEC=E2=80=99s mission to do it for them. The old system =
is that you opt in to public markets to have access to regular investors, a=
t the cost of extensive regulation, or you opt out, deal with sophisticated=
 investors, and do what you want as long as it=E2=80=99s not fraud. But the=
 Gensler SEC=E2=80=99s view is, no, private funds are important, so the SEC=
 can step in to manage their relationship with their clients.=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, the view is that the SEC is not primarily=
 a regulator of the=C2=A0<em>public=C2=A0</em>financial markets, the ones t=
hat are open and accessible to everyone and that some companies and funds v=
oluntarily access. The view is that the SEC is primarily a regulator of the=
=C2=A0<em>important=C2=A0</em>financial markets, the ones where the money i=
s, and if you are big enough there is no way to avoid its regulation.</p><t=
