om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bitfinex</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you have $10,000 in your bank accou=
nt, and thieves hack into your account and drain all of the money, and you =
go to your bank and establish that that=E2=80=99s what happened, and the ha=
ckers get away successfully, what will the bank do? The three main theoreti=
cally possible answers are:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; paddi=
ng-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The ba=
nk will give you the $10,000 back and eat the loss.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">It won=E2=80=99t, and you will eat the loss.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bank will give you some of the money back,=
 and you will split the loss.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which o=
ne it chooses will be determined mostly by regulation and somewhat by how e=
ffectively you complain, but none of that is the point here. The point is t=
hat what will <em>not </em>happen is:</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=C2=
=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A04. The bank will say =E2=80=9CWell the <em>dollars </em>ar=
e gone, but we can credit you with 10,000 Theft Bucks, enjoy!=E2=80=9D</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not even sure I know what that sentence me=
ans. But let me try. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/26666543.270608/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMTktMDYtMTgvZmFjZWJvb2std2lsbC1tYWtlLXRoZS1tb25leS1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDI=
xMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B3c4c12d0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> A bank is a system of computers</a> that keep lists of =
people who have stuff. For the most part, your entry on the list shows how =
many U.S. dollars you have at the bank. There is an important sense in whic=
h this entry means =E2=80=9Cthe number of U.S. dollars that the bank has to=
 pay you when you ask,=E2=80=9D but there is a more important sense in whic=
h it doesn=E2=80=99t. Most people=E2=80=99s primary interaction with their =
bank is not=C2=A0<em>withdrawing paper money</em>; for most people, the num=
ber next to their name on the bank=E2=80=99s list simply=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0<=
/em>the number of dollars that they have. If they want to spend those dolla=
rs, they do it by sending electronic messages telling the bank to decrement=
 the number next to their name and increment the number next to someone els=
e=E2=80=99s name; the dollars never leave the banking system=E2=80=99s comp=
uters,=C2=A0never become paper money,=C2=A0always remain numbers on lists. =
The number on the list is not the number of dollars that the bank has to gi=
ve you if you ask; it is the number of dollars that you have already. =E2=
=80=9CDollars=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>entries on the bank=E2=80=99s=
 list.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank controls the computers, so =
it is a little tempting to say that it could put any number it wants next t=
o your name. It can=E2=80=99t, though, for important reasons of regulation =
and tradition and, you know, the whole banking system would crumble if the =
bank just made up numbers arbitrarily. Well, it would crumble if the bank j=
ust made up numbers=C2=A0<em>of U.S. dollars</em>. U.S. dollars are very im=
portant and widely accepted and there is a huge financial and regulatory ap=
paratus built up around the function (banking) of keeping lists of them. Bu=
t the bank could make up=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>numbers on=C2=A0<em>other=
=C2=A0</em>lists. The bank could say =E2=80=9Cevery time you use an ATM we =
will give you 10 loyalty points,=E2=80=9D and then it could keep a list of =
customers and their loyalty points, and then one day it could say =E2=80=9C=
also we=E2=80=99ll give you 20 loyalty points every time you smile at a tel=
ler=E2=80=9D without any particularly serious implications for the banking =
system.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so you could=C2=A0<em>just a=
bout=C2=A0</em>imagine discovering that your account was hacked and that yo=
ur $10,000 is gone, and going to the bank and saying =E2=80=9Chey your list=
 says I have $0 but I should have $10,000,=E2=80=9D and the bank saying =E2=
=80=9Cwell your entry on that list of dollars=C2=A0was decremented to $0 us=
ing the established procedures of banking, and we cannot reverse those proc=
edures because that would mess everything up, but we will write <em>another=
=C2=A0</em>list,=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>of dollars, but of something else =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0call it Theft Bucks =E2=80=94=C2=A0that we just made up, and=
 we can put 10,000 next to your name on that list, does that help?=E2=80=9D=
 And you will say, no, it absolutely does not, because dollars can be used =
to pay rent and buy sandwiches, while Theft Bucks are a thing that the bank=
 made up just now.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this is becaus=
e there is a very stark binary, in traditional banking, between=C2=A0<em>do=
llars</em>, which are money, and=C2=A0<em>other stuff</em>, which is not. M=
ove this bank into the world of=C2=A0<em>cryptocurrency</em>=C2=A0and the s=
ituation gets much hazier. Crypto tokens can be created arbitrarily, in a s=
ense all of them are money, in another sense none of them are, and there is=
 a continuum between the ones that feel a lot like money and the ones that =
don=E2=80=99t. If you have an account at a crypto exchange and it contains =
